{
  "texts": [
    "We hope that the insights in our paper contribute to a better understanding of the mechanisms that govern how LLMs hallucinate, and principles for controlling these hallucinations.",
    "A number of works have documented the tendency of LLMs to hallucinate factually incorrect responses (Kalai and Vempala, 2023; Bubeck et al., 2023; Kadavath et al., 2022; Agrawal et al., 2023).",
    "Additionally, studies have investigated the conditions under which hallucinations occur and how LLMs behave in such instances.",
    "In particular, LLMs tend to hallucinate more frequently when queried on knowledge that is rarely mentioned in their training data (Mallen et al., 2023; Kandpal et al., 2023).",
    "Furthermore, LLM predictions tend to be moderately calibrated (Kadavath et al., 2022; Zhao et al., 2021; Tian et al., 2023b), and their inter-nal representations seem to reflect some awareness of model uncertainty (Liu et al., 2023; Azaria and Mitchell, 2023)."
  ]
}